Preliminary Traffic Impact Study and Parking Assessment
Kimley-Horn and Associates, Inc. (Kimley-Horn) was retained by the City of Virginia
Beach Strategic Growth Area (SGA) department to perform a traffic impact study (TIS)
and parking assessment for a proposed Virginia Beach Arena, as presented and described
in the Virginia Beach Entertainment + Sports Arena proposal (USM Proposal) dated
February 14, 2014 submitted by United States Management, LLC. The Virginia Beach
Arena, or as commonly referred to herein as the arena, is proposed to be located adjacent
to the existing Virginia Beach Convention Center between 19
Boulevard. The background information used for the traffic impact study and parking
assessment was mostly obtained from the Virginia Beach Entertainment + Sports Arena
proposal (USM Proposal) dated February 14, 2014 submitted by United States
Management (USM), LLC and/or conversations with the USM team.
The primary site being planned to house the arena, parking, and plaza amenities is
approximately 20 acres and is currently occupied by the Virginia Beach Convention
Center surface parking, Tidewater Veterans Memorial Park, the Lighthouse Center, and
undeveloped land. In general, project site is bound by 19
Beach Boulevard to the south, Monroe Avenue to the east and Birdneck Road to the west.
The general scope of services of this traffic impact study and parking assessment
involves the analysis of an approximate 550,000-square foot arena. Initially, the arena
will be constructed with 15,500 permanent seats with the ability to accommodate up to
18,000 seats through temporary scaffolding for a limited number of events over a two or
three year period. Based on USM projections, it is anticipated that the arena will host
approximately 135 to 150 events per year. Attendance levels will range per event, but it
is anticipated that approximately 90-percent of events will draw 7,500 attendees or less
and the remaining events will draw up to 15,500. The arena seating capacity will be
expanded to 18,000 seats on rare occasions for special events, expected to occur 1-3
times every two to three years. This study considers a design event of 13,950 attendees

plus employees during the off-peak/shoulder season of the Oceanfront Resort Area

several intersections, pedestrian accommodations, and modification of traffic signals,
temporary signage, police control during events, off-site parking and shuttle service.

Traffic generation potential for the arena was determined based on review of data from

arena events but also contains useful information pertaining to event seasonality and

assuming 90-percent capacity. A 10-percent attendance reduction is consistent with ULI
methodology and consistent with sold-out concerts at the Farm Bureau Live
Amphitheater. ULI also suggests a 0.03 employee to seat ratio for events which equates
to approximately 420 employees; however, it was unclear whether that ratio only
pertained to staffing inside the arena and not inclusive of security and parking
management. Therefore, Kimley-Horn derived employee and support staff as shown in

staying at the Oceanfront Resort Area, and the weather is more permitting for a higher
(farther) walking tolerance. Therefore, the vehicular mode split is likely lower in the
summer months, but this analysis considered a peak event during the off season of the
The vehicle occupancy for attendees was estimated to be 2.75 people per vehicle.
Through the various resources compiled, this number varies per event but an average of
2.75 people per vehicle is a commonly used industry rate. The supplemental data to
support this rate is provided in the Appendix.
It was assumed that 95-percent of the employees and support staff would arrive prior to
the peak ingress hour and would leave after the peak egress hour. Of the attendees, 70-
percent were assumed to arrive in the peak ingress hour prior to the event with the
remaining 30-percent arriving early to enjoy the amenities of the Oceanfront Resort Area
or arrive after the event begins. During event unloading, it was assumed that 85-percent
would depart the event during the peak egress hour with the remaining 15-percent leaving
prior to the end of the event or staying in the Oceanfront Resort Area after the event. No
reductions were applied for completing the parking analysis since all arena-related
vehicles have to be accounted for and do not matter when they arrive.

traffic volumes used for the peak ingress and egress analysis.

A parking analysis was performed to determine the parking space requirements to support
the Virginia Beach Arena. Prior to site trip assignment and traffic analysis, the parking
requirements had to first be determined since the parking locations are the destinations
and origins of the new arena site trips, not the arena itself.
The parking analysis was performed for a design attendance of 13,950 guests during the
off-peak/shoulder season of the Oceanfront Resort Area using the assumptions described
above. Additionally, a parking analysis was performed for an event during the peak
season of the Oceanfront Resort Area. Based on conversations with USM, an event
during the peak Oceanfront Resort Area season is not anticipated to exceed 7,500
attendees. The same mode split and vehicle ridership assumptions were applied to this
The current conceptual site plan for the arena includes only surface parking around the
arena which includes existing Virginia Beach Convention Center surface lots. The
current surface parking inventory for the Virginia Beach Convention Center is
approximately 2,200 parking spaces; however, when built the arena will occupy and
remove a portion of that inventory. The total surface parking that will surround the
Virginia Beach Convention Center and arena is approximately 2,770 spaces, after
For both parking analysis scenarios, a new 400-space surface parking lot is recommended
to be constructed on the city-owned block bound by Arctic Avenue, Baltic Avenue, 19th
Street, and 20th Street (former Treasurer’s site). During non-events and/or smaller
events, this surface parking lot will support the Oceanfront Resort Area.

A significant inventory of parking spaces exists in the Resort Area in the Central Beach
District. Based on the economic impacts of providing additional parking and the
availability of parking during the shoulder and off peak resort seasons, this inventory was
evaluated to support the arena in addition to the proposed parking in immediate proximity
A walking tolerance was established based on the Manual on Uniform Traffic Control
Devices (2009) walking pace of 3.5 feet per second per. A maximum walking time of
approximately 15 to 20 minutes was determined appropriate based on review of similar
arenas’ parking proximity. Assuming the walking pace and walking time, this distance
equivalent is approximately to the Dome site. Therefore, the existing off-site parking
inventory was evaluated within this distance as follows:
Public – City of Virginia Beach paid surface lot public parking
Commercial – Privately owned parking lots operated for public parking
Shared – Current single use parking lots (e.g., offices, retail, etc.) with
sufficient/excess inventory for use during special events. The use of these lots
will require a change in city ordinances. The total inventory was assumed to be
50-percent utilized by the arena during design events.
On-Street – Meter controlled spaces. No on-street inventory from adjacent
The public and commercial inventory in this area is utilized by the Oceanfront Resort
Area during the peak season. Since the inventory of total spaces won’t be exclusively
available for arena use, particularly during the peak resort season, Kimley-Horn
evaluated parking data from the City of Virginia Beach Resort Area Parking Strategy
(April 2012) which contained detailed occupancy data for each of the public and
commercial parking lots within this district. From review of this data, it was determined
that parking in the Central Beach District is, on average, approximately 70-percent
occupied during the peak Oceanfront Resort Area season. During the Oceanfront Resort
Area off season, parking is approximately 5-percent utilized on average. These

Preliminary Traffic Impact Study and Parking Assessment
As shown in Table 5-2, a 13,950 attendance level during the off season of the Oceanfront
Resort Area creates a deficit of approximately 12 parking spaces based on the predefined
assumptions. Conversely, a 7,500 attendance level during the peak Oceanfront Resort
Area season results in a parking surplus of approximately 1,400 spaces. It is important to
note, the 2,770 planned on-site spaces can accommodate approximately 7,600 patrons
based on the given assumptions. According to USM, approximately 90-percent of the
events will attract 7,500 attendees or less; therefore, the need for additional off-site
parking will typically be limited to approximately 15 events per year.

Use of shared parking will require a change in city ordinance for the public use of
parking in these facilities. Use of this type of parking is common practice at other
venues and is a management strategy that allows the municipality to reduce
infrastructure costs and provides an opportunity for owners to capitalize on

Preliminary Traffic Impact Study and Parking Assessment
choose not to participate and/or still need reserved parking for their business to
The shared and commercial parking facilities are privately controlled. Most, if
not all, of the commercial parking facilities typically do not operate from October
through April therefore making this inventory unavailable. However, an event
presents the opportunity revenue gains that would otherwise be unrealized during
the offseason of the Oceanfront Resort Area.
Virginia Beach Convention Center and arena management staff will have to work
collaboratively and collectively to manage parking demands and limit concurrent
peak events. Should convention center events precipitate the need for additional
parking beyond the 300 spaces, additional spaces adjacent to the convention
center will be reserved as required to support expected guest attendance levels at
the convention center. From a management and operations perspective, both
adequate parking spaces and their close proximity to the convention center will
need to be further refined by the city.
A shuttle system from off-site parking facilities will be required should
concurrent peak events at both the Arena and convention center occur. Shuttles
will have to operate with relatively short headways due to the condensed peak
arrival of attendees. This issue will also need to be addressed by the city as part
of the parking management and operations for the two facilities.

The Virginia Beach Arena will be accessible via an extensive network of roads. The
primary facility providing access to the arena site area will be I-264. Significant
percentages of traffic will also access the development along Birdneck Road via Laskin
Road and General Booth Boulevard. Virginia Beach Boulevard/17
Street are major east/west corridors; and Birdneck Road, Parks
Avenue, Arctic Avenue, and Pacific Avenue are major north/south corridors providing
access to the development. Multiple signalized and unsignalized full access driveways, as
well as multiple partial access driveways are proposed to serve the development.
Driveways into the site will primarily be accessible via 19
Virginia Beach Boulevard. The major driveways will have three lanes to allow two lanes
into the site and one lane out during event loading, and vice versa for event unloading.
There are three proposed internal site roads connecting Virginia Beach Boulevard and
Street, and one connecting Virginia Beach Boulevard to Parks Avenue. As
proposed, there are four parking lot access points along Virginia Beach Boulevard (two
existing; two proposed) and three access points along 19
